@XeroSumGames Any questions just feel free. I've been an Indie Comic Book fanatic for 30 years this year actually. And besides some attempts in High School I've been making comics for twenty two years, though my projects tend to be a bit more out there, I have experience across the board.

@XeroSumGames No problem! I'm working on new titles now; one will be 24pgs but releasing the first two as one 48pg issue as the price seems to be good and I like that flipbook feel. The other is more an anthology so clocking in about 56pgs, but about to go to print w/them soon, so we'll see!

@XeroSumGames I am not the artist, but in the past we did it because of printing costs. We were working on a graphic novel and releasing it in issues, which first we did 48 for 36pgs content & extras, then it was most cost efficient to do more, but this is going off prices from a bit back.

In 2009-2012 I was working with @ComiXology and co-created @PowerPlayComic which was the first to be developed for Guided View Native format as it came to be known. Sadly digital comics weren't there yet, so I stepped away for a bit to create #TEAMUPinTIMESPACE & @TURBOxTHRUST

Just for backstory, I was with my dad was at the Javits in 1992 and we were showing off what he called 'Scanimation' which was artwork scanned in, colored in Photoshop 1, animated in pre-Macromedia Flash, with Midi file music set to it. More a early Motion Comic but pioneering!

I feel like I want to make a documentary about digital comics. It makes me so mad to see so much hate on them, especially from people who are otherwise pleasant and solid comic book readers. Print will always be there, but it will become more of a niche market.
